## M22.1(5/8): value-yielding `try INDENT body OUTDENT` block is reserved in V1.
##
## Per GPT-5.5 entry 39 (M22.1 "fake-surface audit"): the block-
## form fallibility construct (`r = try INDENT body OUTDENT
## catch |e| INDENT body OUTDENT`) parsed cleanly and walked
## through sema/ownership, but emit had no handler — it fell
## through to a default arm producing
## `@compileError("rig: emitter does not yet support
## try_block")`. The user saw a Zig compile error inside Rig-
## generated code, not a Rig diagnostic. That's exactly the
## fake-surface anti-pattern M22.1 closes.
##
## V1 fallibility surface (kept):
##   - `expr!`        — propagate (lowers to Zig `try expr`)
##   - `expr catch |e| recovery`  — inline single-expression catch
##
## The block form needs a real design pass (value-position vs
## statement, catch-binding scoping, resource-aware drop on
## error path, interaction with M20e auto-drop guards) and is
## deferred to a future arc. Until then, V1 rejects it cleanly.

fun may_fail() -> Int!
  return 42

sub main()
  r = try               # error: value-yielding try block reserved
    may_fail()!
  catch |e|
    0
  print(r)
